  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **unlawful** in most countries around the world. It is considered a serious financial crime and is typically punishable by law. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained funds (often from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or terrorism) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This is done through a series of transactions or financial maneuvers to \"clean\" the money.\n\n### Key reasons why money laundering is illegal:\n1. **Undermines the financial system**: Money laundering erodes the integrity of financial institutions and markets.\n2. **Promotes criminal activity**: It enables criminals to profit from illegal activities and reinvest those profits into further crimes.\n3. **Economic harm**: It can destabilize economies by distorting markets and evading taxes.\n4. **Legal compliance**: Financial institutions are required to follow anti-money laundering (AML) regulations to prevent and detect such activities.\n\n### International Efforts to Combat Money Laundering:\nOrganizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorism financing. Many countries have implemented AML laws and regulations to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.\n\nIf you suspect or encounter money laundering, it is important to report it to the relevant authorities.",
